Two zero eigenvalues correspond to directions along the manifold of equilibria. An analysis shows that all disease-free equilibria are linearly stable if S(0) ≤ 1/r(1 − ε), and unstable otherwise. At this bifurcation value, a third eigenvalue crosses the imaginary axis with nonzero speed and gives rise to a different class of endemic (nonzero infected) equilibria. If S(0) ≤ 1/r(1 − ε) no further bifurcations occur, so that these disease-free equilibria are linearly stable independently of the incubation time and isolation protocol.

